\par }{\b\cf2\lang3081 INFINITIVES WITH PREFIXED }{\b\i\cf2\lang3081 A}{\b\cf2\lang3081 -
\par }{\lang1033 The }{\i\lang1033 Markirya}{\lang1033  poem includes two examples of a special infinitive that is marked with the prefix }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 -. (Tolkien first wrote }{\b\lang1033 na}{\lang1033 -, then changed it to }{\b\lang1033 a}{
\lang1033 -, perhaps suggesting that this was a grammatical feature that arose spontaneously in his mind as he worked out the later version of this poem.) The relevant couple of consecutive lines go like this:
\par 
\par \tab }{\b\lang1033 Man cenuva lumbor }{\b\ul\lang1033 ahosta}{\lang1033  "Who shall see [the] clouds }{\ul\lang1033 gather}{\lang1033 ,"
\par \tab }{\b\lang1033 Menel }{\b\ul\lang1033 ac\'fana}{\lang1033 ... "the heavens }{\ul\lang1033 bending}{\lang1033 ...[?]"
\par 
\par The verbs involved are the A-stems }{\b\lang1033 hosta}{\lang1033 - "to gather" and }{\b\lang1033 c\'fana}{\lang1033 - "to bend". What is the function of the }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 -prefix here occurring?
\par }\pard \fi708\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright {\lang1033 Tolkien provided a brief, rather obscure note about it: "When the bare stem of the verb is used (as after 'see' or 'hear') as infinitive [}{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 
-] is prefixed if the noun is the object not the subject" (MC:223). There are at least two possible interpretations of this, but the "traditional" interpretation \endash  reflected in many post-Tolkien texts \endash  goes like
 this: Following sense-verbs (like "see", "watch", "hear" etc.) we will typically find some noun that is the }{\i\lang1033 object}{\lang1033  of the sense-verb in question. In the examples above, }{\b\lang1033 lumbor}{\lang1033  "clouds" and }{
\b\lang1033 Menel}{\lang1033  "the heavens" are the }{\i\lang1033 objects}{\lang1033  (not the subjects!) of the verb }{\b\lang1033 cenuva}{\lang1033 , "shall see". Nonetheless, these verbs are also the logical }{\i\lang1033 subjects}{\lang1033 
 of the verbs "to gather" and "to bend": The clouds gather, the heavens bend. So to express what an object }{\i\lang1033 is itself}{\lang1033  }{\i\lang1033 doing}{\lang1033  while it is the subject of another verb, you use an infinitive with a prefixed }
{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 -. In other words, }{\b\lang1033 man cenuva lumbor }{\b\ul\lang1033 ahosta}{\lang1033  is the Quenya way of saying "who shall see [the] clouds }{\ul\lang1033 as they gather}{\lang1033 
". But unlike "gather" in this English circumlocution, }{\b\lang1033 ahosta}{\lang1033  remains an infinitive, as is clearly seen by the fact that it does not receive the plural ending -}{\b\lang1033 r}{\lang1033  even though its logical subject (}{
\b\lang1033 lumbor}{\lang1033  "clouds") is plural.
\par We may wonder how the prefix }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 - would be added to a verbal stem beginning in a vowel, especially in }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 -. As suggested by Nancy Martsch in her }{\i\lang1033 Basic Quenya}{\lang1033 
, it may sometimes be best to slip in a hyphen, for instance in a sentence like }{\b\lang1033 cennen i n\'eds }{\b\ul\lang1033 a-anta}{\b\lang1033  }{\lang1033 [?] }{\b\lang1033 i seldon parma}{\lang1033 , "I saw the woman }{\ul\lang1033 give}{\lang1033 
 the boy a book".
\par It is also uncertain how the prefix }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 - would be added to primary verbs. A verb like (say) }{\b\lang1033 mat}{\lang1033 - "to eat" would probably include the ending -}{\b\lang1033 \'eb}{\lang1033 
 in its "stem" form, just as it does when it functions as an infinitive. Of course we may prefix }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 - and build a sentence like }{\b\lang1033 tirnen i Naucor }{\b\ul\lang1033 amat\'eb}{\lang1033  = "I watched the Dwarves }{
\ul\lang1033 eat}{\lang1033 " (= "I watched the Dwarves }{\i\lang1033 as they ate}{\lang1033 "). However, a form like }{\b\lang1033 amat\'eb}{\lang1033 
 would be accented on the first syllable, on the prefix itself. Perhaps we should ignore the normal stress rules and let the accent fall on the syllable following the prefix (the spelling }{\b\lang1033 a-mat\'eb}{\lang1033  could be employed to sugges
t this)? Actually, the }{\i\lang1033 Markirya}{\lang1033  poem contains a relevant example involving the verb }{\b\lang1033 cir}{\lang1033 - "to sail", but in this example, the prefix }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 
- is not used at all. Correcting some likely misreadings (}{\i\lang1033 a}{\lang1033  in Tolkien's manuscript thrice being misread as }{\i\lang1033 e}{\lang1033 ), this line would go: }{\b\lang1033 Man cenuva f\'e1na cirya m\'e9tima hrastallo }{
\b\ul\lang1033 c\'edra}{\lang1033  = "Who shall see a white ship }{\ul\lang1033 sail}{\lang1033  from the last shore[?]" (Tolkien's poetic translation in MC:214 reads "who shall see a white ship leave the last shore" \endash 
 but it is clear what the literal meaning is.) The overall construction is very similar to the examples cited above; the "white ship" is the }{\i\lang1033 object}{\lang1033  of the verb }{\b\lang1033 cenuva}{\lang1033 
 = "shall see", but it is also the logical }{\i\lang1033 subject}{\lang1033  of the verb }{\b\lang1033 cir}{\lang1033 - "to sail". The latter is here simply constructed as a "continuative" stem, similar in form to the "present" or "continuous" tense: }{
\b\lang1033 c\'edra}{\lang1033 . So we must assume that "I watched the Dwarves }{\ul\lang1033 eat}{\lang1033 " could similarly be expressed as }{\b\lang1033 tirnen i Naucor }{\b\ul\lang1033 m\'e1ta}{\lang1033 
, and I think I would prefer this construction to the uncertain }{\b\lang1033 amat\'eb}{\lang1033 -form.
\par Of course, we may then ask why a simple "continuative" stem cannot replace the infinitive with prefixed }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 - }{\i\lang1033 everywhere}{\lang1033 . The verbs }{\b\lang1033 hosta}{\lang1033 - "to gather" and }{\b\lang1033 c\'fana}{
\lang1033 - "to collect" would presumably produce the forms }{\b\lang1033 host\'eba}{\lang1033  and }{\b\lang1033 c\'fan\'eba}{\lang1033 . Why, then, cannot "who shall see the clouds }{\ul\lang1033 gather}{\lang1033 , the heavens }{\ul\lang1033 bending}{
\lang1033 ?" be expressed as }{\b\lang1033 man cenuva lumbor }{\b\ul\lang1033 host\'eba}{\b\lang1033 , Menel }{\b\ul\lang1033 c\'fan\'eba}{\lang1033 ? Why did Tolkien use the forms }{\b\lang1033 ahosta}{\lang1033 , }{\b\lang1033 ac\'fana}{\lang1033 
 instead? Of course, for all we know, both constructions could be equally possible, and Tolkien simply picked the one that came into his head first, or the one that fit the meter of his poem better.
\par However, "Gildor Inglorion" has suggested a new interpretation of the function of the }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 - prefix that would allow us to explain all the attested forms. We have already quoted Tolkie
n's note that "when the bare stem of the verb is used (as after 'see' or 'hear') as infinitive [}{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 
-] is prefixed if the noun is the object not the subject" (MC:223). Does he mean: when the "noun" (that is, the object of the main verb of the sentence) is the logical object \endash  not the subject \endash  }{\i\lang1033 of the infinitive itself}{
\lang1033 ? If so, it is obvious why the }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 -prefix is not used in a sentence like "who shall see a white ship }{\ul\lang1033 sail}{\lang1033 ...", for the ship is the logical }{\i\lang1033 subject}{\lang1033 
 of the verb "sail", not the object. This interpretation would mean that the verbs }{\b\lang1033 hosta}{\lang1033 - "gather" and }{\b\lang1033 c\'fana}{\lang1033 - "bend" are actually }{\i\lang1033 transitive}{\lang1033  in the examples where the }{
\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 - prefix occurs, not intransitive as in the English translation: "Who shall see the clouds gather, the heavens bending?" In English, it is just
 the clouds themselves that "gather" or assemble, and the heavens themselves that "bend"; they don't "gather" or "bend" something else.
\par Yet }{\b\lang1033 hosta}{\lang1033 - is also glossed "collect", which is clearly transitive. Of course, this verb could be both transitive and intransitive, just like at least one other verb in -}{\b\lang1033 ta}{\lang1033  (}{\b\lang1033 orta}{\lang1033 
- = transitive "raise" or intransitive "rise"). But if }{\b\lang1033 hosta}{\lang1033 - is taken as meaning "gather" in the transitive sense of "collect", and the prefix }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 - indicates that the "noun" next to the infinitive is 
"the object not the subject" of this verb, then }{\b\lang1033 man cenuva lumbor ahosta[?]}{\lang1033  actually means "who shall see the clouds }{\i\lang1033 being gathered?}{\lang1033 " Similarly, }{\b\lang1033 man cenuva...Menel ac\'fana}{\lang1033 
 would actually mean "who shall see...the heavens }{\i\lang1033 being bent?}{\lang1033 " By this interpretation of the }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 - prefix, our home-made example }{\b\lang1033 tirnen i Naucor amat\'eb}{\lang1033  would }{\i\lang1033 not}{
\lang1033  mean "I watched the Dwarves eat", but rather "I watched the Dwarves being eaten"! The prefix }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 - would indicate that the noun in front of the infinitive is actually to be taken as "the o
bject not the subject" of the eating concerned.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright {\lang1033 
\par Perhaps we shall never know with certainty which of these two interpretations is correct. It may very well be that the prefix }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 - (variant }{\b\lang1033 na}{\lang1033 
-) was spontaneously invented when Tolkien worked out the latest version of the }{\i\lang1033 Markirya}{\lang1033  poem, and that it occurs nowhere else in his notes.
