\par }{\b\cf2\lang3081 ELISION OF FINAL VOWELS
\par }{\lang1033 The greeting }{\b\lang1033 elen s\'edla l\'famenn' omentielvo}{\lang1033  "a star shines on the hour of our meeting" exemplifies a frequent, but not obligatory feature of Quenya phonology: 
When a word ends in a vowel and the next word begins in one, the former vowel may drop out. Thus the final -}{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033  of }{\b\lang1033 l\'famenna}{\lang1033  "on [the] hour" is omitted before the initial }{\b\lang1033 o}{\lang1033 - of }
{\b\lang1033 omentielvo}{\lang1033  "of our meeting". In Elendil's Oath occur the words }{\b\lang1033 tenn' Ambar-metta}{\lang1033 , "until the end of the world", the preposition }{\b\lang1033 tenna}{\lang1033  "until" being reduced to }{\b\lang1033 tenn}
{\lang1033 ' before the initial }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 - of }{\b\lang1033 Ambar-metta}{\lang1033  "World-end = the end of the world". Occasionally, this phenomenon may even result in new, seemingly unitary words, as when the same preposition }{
\b\lang1033 tenna}{\lang1033  "until" and the noun }{\b\lang1033 oio}{\lang1033  "endless period" are contracted: }{\b\lang1033 tennoio}{\lang1033  (for }{\b\lang1033 tenn' oio}{\lang1033 ) "forever" (UT:305, 317).
\par \tab Naturally, such omission of final vowels is especially common when one word ends in a vowel that is similar or identical to the initial vowel of the next word (like the omission of -}{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033  before }{\b\lang1033 o}{\lang1033 - and 
}{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 - in the examples above). In }{\i\lang1033 F\'edriel's Song}{\lang1033  as printed in LR:72, there is a dot under some final vowels, which may be taken as a sign that they are to be elided. Replacing the dot with underlin
ing and not otherwise altering the original spelling of this "Qenya" text, we may quote the relevant phrases like this: 1) }{\b\lang1033 Ilu Il\'favatar en k\'e1r}{\b\ul\lang1033 e}{\b\lang1033  eldain}{\lang1033  "Il\'fa
vatar made the world for Elves"; here the final -}{\b\lang1033 e}{\lang1033  of }{\b\lang1033 k\'e1r}{\b\ul\lang1033 e}{\b\lang1033  }{\lang1033 "made" is apparently omitted before an identical vowel; 2) }{\b\lang1033 \'edr}{\b\ul\lang1033 e}{\b\lang1033 
 ilqa y\'e9va n\'f3tina}{\lang1033  "when all is counted" and }{\b\lang1033 \'edr}{\b\ul\lang1033 e}{\b\lang1033  Anarinya qeluva}{\lang1033  "when my sun shall fail"; here we have omission of final -}{\b\lang1033 e}{\lang1033  before }{\b\lang1033 i}{
\lang1033  and }{\b\lang1033 a}{\lang1033 , respectively; 3) }{\b\lang1033 eny\'e1r}{\b\ul\lang1033 e}{\b\lang1033  tar i tyel}{\lang1033  "in that day beyond the end", which if we interpret Tolkien's
 intentions correctly is a unique example of a final vowel being elided before an initial }{\i\lang1033 consonant}{\lang1033  in the next word (}{\b\lang1033 tar}{\lang1033 ).
\par \tab Yet such omission of final vowels is clearly not necessary to produce correct Quenya, which is why we ignored it in the exercises of this course. The phrase }{\b\lang1033 l\'famenn' omentielvo}{\lang1033  is }{\i\lang1033 twice}{\lang1033 
 attested in its full form }{\b\lang1033 l\'famenna omentielvo}{\lang1033  (WJ:367, Letters:424). Our small corpus also contains examples of a final vowel persisting even where the next word begins in an }{\i\lang1033 identical}{\lang1033  vowel \endash 
 as in the sentence }{\b\lang1033 aur\'eb entuluva}{\lang1033  "day shall come again", cited in the }{\i\lang1033 Silmarillion}{\lang1033 , chapter 20. Presumably this could also be shortened (}{\b\lang1033 aur' entuluva}{\lang1033 ),
 but not necessarily so. Elision of final vowels would probably be most common in the spoken language, and in poetry it may also be useful to be able to get rid of a syllable where the poetic meter demands it.
